<h1>About This Example</h1>
<p>
  This example demonstrates <strong>golit</strong> as Rack middleware in a
  Ruby application running inside a Podman / Docker container.
  The <code>GolitMiddleware</code> class works identically with Rails,
  Sinatra, Hanami, or any Rack-compatible framework.
</p>

<h2>The Pipeline</h2>
<ol>
  <li>The Rack app renders ERB templates containing Lit web components</li>
  <li><code>GolitMiddleware</code> intercepts the HTML response</li>
  <li>It writes the HTML to a temp file and runs <code>golit transform</code></li>
  <li>golit renders each custom element to Declarative Shadow DOM</li>
  <li>The browser receives pre-rendered HTML that hydrates instantly</li>
</ol>

<my-counter count="42"></my-counter>

<p>
  Try viewing the page source&mdash;you&rsquo;ll see a
  <code>&lt;template shadowrootmode="open"&gt;</code> inside each
  <code>&lt;my-counter&gt;</code>, proving it was server-side rendered.
</p>

<h2>Using with Rails</h2>
<p>
  Drop the middleware into any Rails app:
</p>
<pre><code># config/application.rb
config.middleware.use GolitMiddleware,
  golit_bin: '/usr/local/bin/golit',
  defs_dir:  Rails.root.join('bundles').to_s</code></pre>
